        </p>
        <h2 id="installing-terraform">Installing Terraform ‚öôÔ∏è</h2>
        <p>
          To get started, you first need to install Terraform on your system.
          Terraform provides installation guides for all major operating systems
          on their <a href="https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/install"
            >official website</a
          >. Just follow the steps for your platform, and once installed, you
          can verify it by running:
        </p>
        <CodeContainer
          ><pre><code class="language-bash">terraform -v
</code></pre></CodeContainer
        >
        <h2 id="setting-up-aws-credentials">Setting Up AWS Credentials üîë</h2>
        <p>
          Before using Terraform with AWS, you need to set up your AWS Access
          Key and Secret Key. Here's a quick guide:
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            Log in to your <a href="https://aws.amazon.com/console"
              >AWS Management Console</a
            >.
          </li>
          <li>Navigate to IAM (Identity and Access Management).</li>
          <li>
            Go to Users, select your user, and click on the Security credentials
            tab.
          </li>
          <li>
            Create Access keys by clicking Create access key. You‚Äôll get an
            Access Key ID and Secret Access Key‚Äîstore these securely.
          </li>
        </ol>
        <p>
          Add them to your system‚Äôs environment variables for Terraform to use,
          or use the AWS CLI for easier credential management.
        </p>
        <h2 id="set-up-terraform-and-create-an-s3-bucket-in-aws">
          Set Up Terraform and Create an S3 Bucket in AWS üì¶
        </h2>
        <p>
          In this section, we‚Äôll use Terraform to create an S3 bucket. Here‚Äôs
          the process.
        </p>
        <h3 id="step-1-initialize-your-working-directory">
          Step 1: Initialize Your Working Directory
        </h3>
        <ol>
          <li>Create a New Directory for your Terraform project:</li>
        </ol>
        <CodeContainer
          ><pre><code class="language-bash">mkdir terraform-s3-demo
cd terraform-s3-demo
</code></pre></CodeContainer
        >
        <ol start="2">
          <li>
            Create Your Terraform Configuration File (usually <code
              >main.tf</code
            >):
          </li>
        </ol>
        <CodeContainer
          ><pre><code class="language-bash">touch main.tf
</code></pre></CodeContainer
        >
        <h3 id="step-2-writing-the-terraform-code">
          Step 2: Writing the Terraform Code
        </h3>
        <p>
          Open <code>main.tf</code> in your favorite editor and add the following
          configuration:
        </p>
        <CodeContainer
          ><pre><code class="language-ruby"># Provider Block
provider "aws" &#123;
  region = "us-east-1" # Specify your region here
&#125;

resource "aws_s3_bucket" "my_bucket" &#123;
  bucket = "my-terraform-demo-bucket-123456"

  tags = &#123;
    Name        = "Terraform Demo S3 Bucket"
    Environment = "Dev"
  &#125;
&#125;
</code></pre></CodeContainer
        >
        <h2 id="applying-the-terraform-configuration">
          Applying the Terraform Configuration üöÄ
        </h2>
        <p>Once you have your configuration ready, it‚Äôs time to run it!</p>
        <h3 id="step-1-initialize-terraform">
          Step 1: Initialize Terraform üõ†Ô∏è
        </h3>
